  "prompt": "Can someone get pregnant 10 days after their period?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible for someone to get pregnant 10 days after their period, depending on their menstrual cycle and ovulation timing. Here's how it works:\n\n1. **Ovulation Timing**: Ovulation typically occurs around day 14 of a 28-day menstrual cycle, but this can vary. If someone has a shorter cycle (e.g., 21 days) or ovulates earlier than average, ovulation could happen closer to day 10 after their period ends.\n\n2. **Sperm Survival**: Sperm can live inside the female reproductive tract for up to 5 days. If intercourse occurs shortly before ovulation, sperm may still be present to fertilize the egg.\n\n3. **Fertility Window**: The fertile window is typically the 5 days leading up to ovulation and the day of ovulation itself. If ovulation occurs around day 10 after the period, conception is possible.\n\nHowever, if the person has a longer cycle or ovulates later, the likelihood of pregnancy 10 days after their period may be lower. Every individual's cycle is different, so it's essential to track ovulation (using methods like basal body temperature, ovulation predictor kits, or cervical mucus changes) for a clearer understanding of fertility.",
